<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Inline Assessment MathML 1.4//EN" "http://oli.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_inline_assessment_mathml_1_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="_u1_m2_digestive_identify_extra_inline"><title>Identifying Digestive Organs: Extra Questions</title><page id="b7e011c7356f49dbb6a6df96af8711b0"><title>Assessment Page Title</title><question id="I_u1_m2_digestive_extra_stomach"><body><image id="f6a44c808efb4982bb0bfbb20ab266e4" src="../webcontent/Digestion_identify_stomach.png" alt="" style="inline" vertical-align="middle"><caption><p id="f6bd1cf22ee245e59db3cff2fa5504f9" /></caption><popout enable="false"></popout></image><p id="cc4533c34ea14f289e91f225e41b2477">The arrow in the image above points to the <input_ref input="stomach" />. </p><p id="d2f6db86deb6477f98ff539fefdd017f">This organ&apos;s primary role begins when it takes the <input_ref input="bolus" /> from the esophagus and <input_ref input="mixes" /> it with enzymes and digestive juices.</p></body><fill_in_the_blank shuffle="true" id="stomach"><choice value="liver">liver</choice><choice value="stomach">stomach</choice><choice value="pancreas">pancreas</choice><choice value="small_intestine">small intestine</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank shuffle="true" id="bolus"><choice value="enzymes">enzymes</choice><choice value="bolus">bolus</choice><choice value="nutrients">nutrients</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank shuffle="true" id="mixes"><choice value="absorbs">absorbs</choice><choice value="mixes">mixes</choice><choice value="secretes">secretes</choice></fill_in_the_blank><part id="I_u1_m2_digestive_extra_stomach_p1" score_out_of="1"><skillref idref="_u1_describe_digestive_structure_SKILL" /><response match="stomach" score="1" input="stomach"><feedback><p id="ce96b7a263ac4e1f99d02cb35400906c">Correct. The arrow points to the stomach, which mixes the bolus with digestive enzymes and other juices.</p></feedback></response><response match="liver" score="0" input="stomach"><feedback><p id="cfa0aeaf12ef4d2e85b5c5e788abac6d">This is not correct. The liver is involved in digestion but it is the stomach that mixes the bolus with digestive enzymes. </p></feedback></response><response match="pancreas" score="0" input="stomach"><feedback><p id="d964be4507cf450a8b737d7c056cdb79">This is not correct. The pancreas is involved in digestion but it is the stomach that mixes the bolus with digestive enzymes. </p></feedback></response><response match="small_intestine" score="0" input="stomach"><feedback><p id="a2ae2b9c13954a27bee1158bf3cb2993">This is not correct. Look again at the image above. To what organ is the arrow pointing?</p></feedback></response><hint targets="stomach"><p id="d718fd40701345d4b591ef4904320c66">This is a J-shaped organ.</p></hint></part><part id="I_u1_m2_digestive_extra_stomach_p2" score_out_of="1"><skillref idref="_u1_describe_digestive_function_SKILL" /><response match="enzymes" score="0" input="bolus"><feedback><p id="a733f0cfdcbd4fdc97ff5893df251d9c">This is not the best answer. While the salivary glands do produce some enzymes, the stomach receives the bolus from the esophagus.</p></feedback></response><response match="bolus" score="1" input="bolus"><feedback><p id="a30ab174efff4318adee8099a9b8c8e1">Correct. The stomach receives the bolus from the esophagus.</p></feedback></response><response match="nutrients" score="0" input="bolus"><feedback><p id="c6474855794646efbe9f5931b477f9cd">This is not the best answer. While the bolus contains nutrients, these nutrients are not yet broken down sufficiently to be useful. </p></feedback></response><hint targets="bolus"><p id="bb1b6c8d36844f7495972ef0da6a3224">This is the name for a bit of chewed food.</p></hint></part><part id="I_u1_m2_digestive_extra_stomach_p3" score_out_of="1"><skillref idref="_u1_describe_digestive_function_SKILL" /><response match="absorbs" score="0" input="mixes"><feedback><p id="c685fad58efc4fec9799dde194624959">This is incorrect. The lining of the stomach primarily works to keep acids in the stomach. Most of the absorption is carried out by the small intestine. </p></feedback></response><response match="mixes" score="1" input="mixes"><feedback><p id="c03aebd49bd44fb69ee081a1dc8bc457">Correct. The stomach mixes the bolus with digestive enzymes to further break it down. </p></feedback></response><response match="secretes" score="0" input="mixes"><feedback><p id="b9bba80de8d6437db3a79b43df4e42f9">This is not correct. The lining of the stomach primarily works to keep acids within the stomach. </p></feedback></response><hint targets="mixes"><p id="bda29ad1a46444bd988acbf4da766899">This sac churns a large amount of food with digestive juices and gradually releases it into the small intestine</p></hint></part></question></page><page id="a1f48453f6954119b72adebc93be383d"><title>Assessment Page Title</title><question id="I_u1_m2_digestive_extra_liver"><body><image id="a4e0142852d142bcb84baa99ceb138e7" src="../webcontent/Digestion_identify_liver.png" alt="" style="inline" vertical-align="middle"><caption><p id="f159333b03744c479ba1888fe097d206" /></caption><popout enable="false"></popout></image><p id="cdc5dd59de4b4d91890aa69da98af605">The arrow in the image above points to the <input_ref input="liver" />. </p><p id="c2b80e4bba4e488a9e77cb599c077241">This organ <input_ref input="produces" /> bile.</p></body><fill_in_the_blank shuffle="true" id="liver"><choice value="liver">liver</choice><choice value="stomach">stomach</choice><choice value="gall_bladder">gall bladder</choice><choice value="small_intestine">small intestine</choice></fill_in_the_blank><fill_in_the_blank shuffle="true" id="produces"><choice value="stores">stores</choice><choice value="breaks_down">breaks down</choice><choice value="produces">produces</choice></fill_in_the_blank><part id="I_u1_m2_digestive_extra_liver_p1" score_out_of="1"><skillref idref="_u1_describe_digestive_structure_SKILL" /><response match="liver" score="1" input="liver"><feedback><p id="f909bb715c75403a833b39bc12fd30dd">Correct. The arrow points to the liver, which is the largest organ in the digestive system.</p></feedback></response><response match="stomach" score="0" input="liver"><feedback><p id="d0aa5c3427eb446989a5664563bc711d">This is not correct. The arrow points to the liver, which is the largest organ in the digestive system. </p></feedback></response><response match="gall_bladder" score="0" input="liver"><feedback><p id="d041ced66e684a5d8eb2e63ddcb830aa">This is not correct. The arrow points to the liver, which is the largest organ in the digestive system. </p></feedback></response><response match="small_intestine" score="0" input="liver"><feedback><p id="ca804d132d3f44cabb63f83b8e23acb7">This is not correct. The arrow points to the liver, which is the largest organ in the digestive system. </p></feedback></response><hint targets="liver"><p id="c69491a5034344228af649a4d4859f17">This is the largest organ in the digestive system.</p></hint></part><part id="I_u1_m2_digestive_extra_liver_p2" score_out_of="1"><skillref idref="_u1_describe_digestive_function_SKILL" /><response match="stores" score="0" input="produces"><feedback><p id="a6ea07c2e0a541d197888ae7aac429d4">This is not correct. The gall bladder stores bile between meals. The liver produces bile.</p></feedback></response><response match="breaks_down" score="0" input="produces"><feedback><p id="fe3c7791b2284a8abb1e151f611759c7">This is not correct. The liver produces bile. </p></feedback></response><response match="produces" score="1" input="produces"><feedback><p id="a3c79f9cb8824c21b08f5b313d8849b8">Correct. The liver produces bile. </p></feedback></response><hint targets="produces"><p id="d00e0af430894f44958d0c764b5191fd">The gall bladder stores bile between meals.</p></hint></part></question></page></assessment>
